segments.text: I believe it's already connected and now we'll see if it's actually picking up sound in the room.
Let's see, I'll ask some questions.
All of your family is from Texas, right?
You want to take it right here?
Yeah, I'll play it back to you.
And the other Bustamante is very far.
On the other side of Victoria.
On the other side of Victoria.
And it's the house of your mother and father?
But are they all from Mexico?
And what is your father's name?
In what year did they come to the United States?
What was the reason they came?
What kind of work did your father have in Mexico?
He didn't know what kind of work, because there was no work.
What was the reason for the revolution?
How old were you when you came here?
The other boys came when they were little.
And he was telling me something.
We came on foot and then we took the train at night for a while.
The next day we walked on foot.
How long did it take for your uncle to get out of there?
My uncle took about a month or five weeks.
And how was it possible to eat?
Well, almost bread, only bread and water.
Sometimes there was everything, but there was nothing to buy.
My uncle brought money, just limited, little.
Yes, one or two boys came, little ones, my brothers came sick.
Well, if there was nothing to eat, well, give him a doctor and all that, because there was nothing to eat.
And the water, was it good or bad?
Well, what we found, sometimes a little good, sometimes bad.
And what time of year was it?
In this month, the 8th, the 8th of January, the 18th, we passed the royal.
Well, they came to us with fear and they never saw us.
And God did not see us and covered us because there can be no other way.
And for what reason did he decide to leave his people?
At this time, is there a very big, special problem or something else?
Because that year, the uncle decided to go to Taerios.
They had a very different year, Frivi and all.
But they walked hidden until San Antonio.
They came to College Station in a bus.
No, from Laredo they came in a bus.
Locked up, without food, without drink.
That's where those two sick creatures came from.
What year did they arrive at College Station?
The same year, in the same month, yes.
He wanted to know the date of the year, right?
I mean, it seems like the 15th, the 17th.
For what reason did they come here, to Bryan?
No, we were outside of Bryan, at the ranch.
It's a ranch close to here?
But when we came from Mexico, we went to work in a ranch 20 miles away from here.
¿Y su papá fue campesino o comerciante?
No, comenzaron a trabajar en Desenraiz con un... Para limpiar tierra, para sembrar.
Y aquí nos venimos hace unos 25 años, nos venimos para...
But before what, in Bustamante, what kind of work did he have?
Well, just sowing, reed corn, you know.
That's the main thing in Mexico.
Did he have his own land?
We lived there on a ranch and it never rained.
I don't know how we make a living.
They irrigated, they were irrigation lands.
I was with someone else, with the owners of the land.
And then, in 1918, your mother and father went to the United States.
and two sons-in-law, one son-in-law came with their grandparents.
You are Mr. Medina and your other name is?
And his mother and father and the whole family.
And he came to Texas first?
Yes, he was here, he was many years old.
He and her father always lived in the same ranch.
Oh, his family still knows your family.
Because his aunt... My father was from his people.
But she was from Texas and he was from Mexico.
But they were very close people.
And for this reason, your family came to Wheelback during these years.
Just the little kids and they got married.
I don't want to say this because...
He was 18 and I was 16 years old.
He is older than me, 4 years.
How many years does he live in Wheelock?
In what year did you come here to Bryan?
And what kind of work do you have here in Bryan?
The first years, I worked as a baker.
And I worked as a butcher.
Y después buscamos trabajo aquí en él.
Y yo comencé a trabajar en un garage.
Él comenzó a trabajar en College Station, en un comedor, ¿te acuerdas?
Y trabajé una temporada en el garage.
Y luego paré y fui a College Station.
I worked in a dining room, washing dishes, sweeping, mapping.
From there, I would go to the car station, and I would come back to the garage.
And have you ever returned to Mexico to visit?
He retired when he got hurt on his eye.
In what year did you retire?
In what year did he retire?
And you never want to visit Mexico?
Well, no, we don't have money.
And I say that you need money because here the neighbors go and they bring a lot of money.
What kind of house does your family have in Mexico?
Your house, your family's house in Mexico, in Bustamante.
Well, houses like the ones in Aguas Pobres, they look like they're...
No, they're... What's it called, Amara?
They made different houses, but like garbage.
They made carts out of it.
Carrizo, I don't know how they call it.
Have you seen that big bush over there that looks like corn?
That's what I told you it was carrizo.
They dry it and they stop it like this.
And they put leaves like this and then they add carrizo.
You must have seen some when they went to Mexico.
I think I've seen houses like that in Tlamalipas.
I haven't seen him, but his mother and the people from the medical center.
Ah, his mother says all these things.
They put tortillas like this on their arms.
They burned firewood and they put a comal like this and they put tortillas.
And they hid them because they heard them and they came and took them away.
They suffered a lot in Mexico.
That's why he didn't want to go to Mexico.
I do want to go one day.
One day I want to go there.
I want to go to the ranch where my father and mother live.
The two of them are dead.
One day, I want to go back.
This young man is the one who has gone from the whole family to Mexico.
Those two have gone, but this one has been in the family home of his wife.
And from there, he has been to Monterrey and all that.
I don't know, I don't know.
You know, on vacation they go see them.
They've got people in the nest.
His wife, family, they live in the nest.
Then there was nothing to do with him, just the firewood.
Now, my sister-in-law says that there is beauty in some parts.
There were schools there when you were a child?
When the war, there was nothing.
In what year began, how do you say began?
Y su familia vive en este pueblo con la guerra para ocho años?
Pues el papá de él se fue con los soldados.
Y él se quedó a atender la familia.
No, que mi mamá no vente, vamos.
I was older, and the other two were younger.
I don't know what my mother did for us.
He didn't have any money or anything.
And your father was a soldier?
What kind of general was he?
But your father returned to Bustamente in what year?
Yes, he was lucky that he returned.
And then there was nothing to eat, there was nothing, no work.
He had an idea of where there was enough corn to eat.
And he said, before my children, these creatures die of hunger, let's go there.
And so he took us to a place where there was a lot of water, a lot of corn.
People died not of hunger, but of sickness.
Very sick, because they drank river water.
There was no water left to drink from the river.
Yes, I think you live there.
You live in Mexico, I think I know him.
Bustamante is close to Santa Ingracia?
How many miles, more or less, separated are the two places?
How many miles separated are they?
There was a place called La Cruz.
Another place where the train stops.
The train that comes from there, it goes from here to Monterrey, and it stops there at La Cruz.
La Cruz and Santé András are in the middle, not very far, one of the two.
And that's the name of the river, the Santé András River.
It's where a lot of people were sick.
this disease was during the trip?
Yes, well, some of them came, and one of them had already got up, and other sick people came, and my uncle said, well, let's go.
Well, this boy is very bad.
You know, wherever he dies, we bury him.
But all these people would have stayed there.
They started writing to the uncle.
And we, as we were here, he said, my father's name was Ignacio, his name was Juan.
He went and told him, Ignacio, my father is very bad there, my sister, my brother-in-law.
The two of them were from Mexico.
Today we are going to gather this family and the other and we will help you.
Many helped that uncle so that he could bring them.
He left alone with a bag of clothes only for him.
He knew very well that he was going to suffer there.
They were just in a house.
It was dark and it didn't dawn.
He put them all in motion and they all came.
His father, his mother, his grandmother, his grandson, his grandchildren, his grandchildren, because they had already buried three of the virgulas.
There was only one behind the other.
And when they came from there, they came in pain because they had left their daughters buried.
but they were running away from that revolution.
They couldn't eat, they couldn't make their food, because if they made it, they would smell it, they would add tortillas, they would smell it, and they would come and take it away.
If they brought a blanket, they would take it away.
All they wanted was to live.
But his father was already free from the revolution, they had already left him.
The worst thing he did was to leave.
And he transported them by boat.
They didn't go by, you know, by train or something.
One behind the other, one behind the other.
And they were hidden in a house.
And in that house, there was a bus that picked them up to San Antonio.
He sent Ken out of here to bring them.
Do you know what huayines are?
From the family that he had here.
Y todos nos juntamos a dar ropa, a dar comida cuando ellos vinieran.
Y en Guadalini, entre las nieves, muchos veían.
Pero así venían todas cobijaditas de luto, todas muchachas, no muchachas que estas, todas de luto porque habían dejado hermanos, sobrinos, enterrados.
Un tío de él fue afusilado en esa guerra por malicia.
And my mother-in-law cried a lot and said, when I got married, she told me from there, if you saw how sad the revolution is, you don't know.
When they shot my brother, she said, did you know what time it was when the sun came out?
Did you know what time they were going to shoot him?
And where they shot him, so close to our house.
My mom and we were all in that corner, praying, asking God for the brother who was going to be shot.
That uncle of his had just been shot when they came here.
His name was... What was his name?
They just shot them because at that time, even if they didn't go, they would say, you did it, you did it.
And as they grabbed one here, the police, don't talk.
Y después aquí tuvimos que arreglar.
No quisieron echarnos, pero arreglamos y pagamos los...
In these years, there aren't many people on the border to make papers, right?
Now, yes, we have the papers.
But they were reporting for many years that they weren't from here.
It was a bad past, yes.
But they said, well, let's go to Langley.
But in the citizenship papers, there they had to say what the reason was for them to come here.
And they had a very big excuse, because defending life, you know.
But it's a very delicate thing to say that.
But in the scriptures it says that there was a very big reason for them to run away.
And that uncle was the one who saved all those people.
But now you are a citizen.
When I married him, they told me that I had lost my citizenship here.
That he had made me Mexican.
But a lot of people told me, fix your papers, because if you don't fix your papers, he can't be a citizen.
And I fixed my papers, and I said, well, why if I'm here?
At that time, they made one of them.
And I fixed my papers, and he fixed his.
Because with my papers, I made him a citizen.
But that's how my in-laws and their citizens have been doing it.
Many of my brothers-in-law have become citizens.
So he doesn't have to report anything anymore.
He reports his portrait of his land.
And your grandparents, do they like it here?
No, they don't like it anymore.
No, he died, he's buried in a hole.
But when they came here, did they like life here?
One thing they didn't like was that he had put corn tortillas
Y le daban, no, yo no quiero.
La tortilla de harina no la quería, que le hacía mal.
Eso era lo único que no le gustaba a ella.
Lo demás sí, todo le gustaba.
¿Y su mamá y papá también le gusta?
And even if he doesn't like it, he has whatever he wants.
My father is old, but he's still alive.
He still roams around, you know?
What are you going to show him?
He lives not even two blocks from here.
Down behind that golf station, down the road.
You know that golf station over here?
If one of you could take me and introduce me to him,
Sometime during the week, I could call you and ask if it would be a good day.
Because he might like to tell about it, and he could maybe say some things that he would remember having been older than you.
Ah, how nice to make this story about him too.
And then my family came to Texas when I had...
Casi la misma con usted vienen a Texas.
Y después yo fueron a Louisiana para mis estudios en la universidad.
Y me encuentro mi esposo allá.
Él es un, bueno, su familia de Louisiana es un parte, un parte francesa.
or Cajun, a part German, a part Irish.
From Ireland and also from Spain.
And also another part of England and Scotland.
My brother is a teacher in a school out there.
The little one is a teacher in a school out there.
This little boy spent about three or four months in Louisiana National Guard.
He finished college and then he went to Virginia.
There are a lot of French people in Louisiana.
How many children do you have?
Were you the last one to marry?
I'm the last one to marry.
He was the baby one, and then he beat me, and I was the last one, you know, to get married.
And this is one of your sons?
And you know one of our brothers-in-law, they're already there.
What kind of work does he have?
Only he and she live in Love.
And what kind of work does he have?
He works in the shoe shop.
Ah, your son is very handsome.
Does he teach at the college?
Or he teaches at the college here?
And this one, this is my baby.
This is the one on the side.
That's her and him with their family.
Sally and Mamie, and Rich and David and Mamie.
She has a job like him.
He inspects airplanes, he doesn't work, he just inspects airplanes.
Y esto es toda mi familia.
This was the one that was making the noise.
The first one and the last one.
The last one and the first one.
The oldest one and the last one.
It doesn't look like it here.
I'm telling you, baby, you were very pretty when you were little, but now you're very ugly.
Yo le digo, ahora estás muy feo.
Pero mire, cuando nos vinimos para acá, así estaba él.
Y se retrató en una pera ella.
Y ya estábamos con los belices listos para venirnos para acá.
Estos son los dos hermanos y las dos hermanas, las que están ahorita en el hospital.
They married two brothers and two sisters.
They were having a dance, a dance, and they had to wear a kimono.
She, that looks, that's... Oh, she is pretty.
She got those two babies married.
And he's got a little baby, too.
And they've been married five years already.
Is she from here, or is she from somewhere?
Well, she teaches both languages, you know.
Mire, estos son tres hijos de este.
But that's a big one, and there's a second, and there's a third.
One of them, the oldest, is going to get married by the third of November.
He's going to get married with one of his nurses.
Well, their father is muy guapo.
